'''Paul Chester Hoover''' (born April 14, 1976 in [[Columbus, Ohio]]) is an [[United States|American]] professional [[baseball]] [[catcher]] in  the [[Boston Red Sox]] organization. He is officially listed as standing 6 feet 1&nbsp;inch tall, and weighing 220 pounds.

==Professional career==

In 1994 Hoover was drafted by the [[Houston Astros]] in the 64th round of the [[Major League Baseball]] [[Major League Baseball Draft|amateur draft]] however he did not sign. Hoover was drafted by the [[Tampa Bay Rays|Tampa Bay Devil Rays]] in the 23rd round (714th overall) of the [[1997 Major League Baseball Draft|1997 amateur draft]], with whom he signed on June 6, 1997.

On September 29, {{mlby|2007}}, Hoover broke up a potential [[no-hitter]] in the eighth inning with an [[infield]] [[Single (baseball)|single]] to spoil a bid by [[John Maine]] of the [[New York Mets]]. The Mets are one of the few teams in baseball not to have a no-hitter in their history.

On January 7, {{By|2009}}, Hoover signed a minor league contract with an invitation to [[spring training]] with the Philadelphia Phillies.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2009/01/07/sports/BBN-Phillies-Giles.php |title=Hoover signs with Phils |accessdate=2009-01-07 |author=The Associated Press |authorlink=The Associated Press |date=2009-01-07 |work=iht.com}}</ref>  

On October 4, 2009, Hoover hit a walk-off RBI single on the final day of the regular season against the Florida Marlins to give the Phillies a 7-6 victory.

He was outrighted to Triple-A Lehigh Valley on October 28, 2010.

In February 2011, Hoover signed a minor league contract with the Boston Red Sox.<ref>[http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20110202&content_id=16557170&vkey=news_bos&c_id=bos&partnerId=rss_bos Red Sox sign four free agents to Minors deals] MLB.com, February 2, 2011</ref>

Hoover currently holds the MLB record for most seasons by a nonpitcher with 25 or fewer [[plate appearances]] with 6.<ref>[http://www.baseball-reference.com/blog/archives/9926 Most Seasons (Non-P) PA <= 25] baseball-reference.com, February 12, 2011</ref>

